{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T15:22:38.764942", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Valine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.6\n- Feedback: The network is topologically decent and connected, with recognizable hubs and multiple convergent motifs. Environmental interconnection is a relative strength: hydrothermal carbon fixation feeds surface carbonyl/nitrile chemistry, which then feeds biochemical assembly. Mineral specification is partially implied by reaction descriptions, though the provided summary omits explicit agent fields and some steps in non-hydrothermal stages lack needed mechanistic detail. The major weaknesses are chemical rather than graph-theoretic. Most importantly, valine aminonitrile cannot plausibly arise directly from acetaldehyde via Strecker chemistry because acetaldehyde encodes an alanine skeleton, not valine's branched side chain. Likewise, alpha-ketoisovalerate formation from pyruvate plus acetaldehyde is too compressed and unsupported as a single prebiotic step, and the final alpha-ketoisovalerate-to-valine conversion lacks explicit reductant or amino donor definition. Additional issues include an unrealistic HCN source from CO2 plus NH3 alone and an overly vague formaldehyde-to-acetaldehyde surface transformation. As a result, the network does not yet support high confidence target achievement despite good connectivity.\n- Issues: ['Conceptually coherent hydrothermal-to-biochemical route, but the key bottleneck is alpha-ketoisovalerate formation from pyruvate plus acetaldehyde. That C-C bond-forming step is underspecified and not a standard direct prebiotic route. Final amination to valine is plausible in broad terms, but requires a reductant or amino donor not explicitly represented.', 'This is one of the more interpretable routes because pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde and aminonitrile hydrolysis are reasonable. The major issue is Strecker synthesis of valine aminonitrile directly from acetaldehyde, HCN, and NH3: acetaldehyde would more naturally give alanine aminonitrile, not the branched valine aminonitrile.', 'The early hydrothermal section is plausible and well aligned with iron-sulfur world concepts. However, the claimed convergence from formate and acetate into pyruvate is not actually represented by a distinct reaction, and the later branch to alpha-ketoisovalerate remains chemically weak.', 'The hydrothermal generation of small carbonyls is broadly plausible, and aminonitrile hydrolysis is acceptable. But the central aldehyde-to-valine-aminonitrile step is chemically mismatched: acetaldehyde does not encode the isopropyl side chain of valine.', \"This is among the weaker pathways. The conversion of formaldehyde to an 'acetaldehyde-accessible carbonyl pool' is too vague and chemically underdefined, and the downstream Strecker step still uses the wrong aldehyde skeleton for valine.\", 'Dual-input logic is good, but the surface HCN generation reaction from only CO2 and NH3 is not realistic as written, even with TiO2. Combined with the incorrect Strecker substrate assignment, this pathway remains weak.', 'The route is compact but too compressed. It jumps from simple aldehydes to the branched keto acid with insufficient mechanistic support, and the final amination remains underspecified.', 'The HCN reservoir concept is reasonable at network level, but the actual chemistry is weak. HCN generation is poorly specified and valine aminonitrile is not credibly obtained from acetaldehyde.', 'There is useful redundancy around the carbonyl hub, but several interconversions are not chemically clean. The formaldehyde-to-acetaldehyde step is especially problematic, and the branched keto acid synthesis remains the central weakness.', 'This is the best integrated environmental route because it clearly spans hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical stages. However, it still depends on a weak HCN source and an insufficiently justified branched-chain keto acid construction.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Valine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network targets valine through two chemically distinct but connected prebiotic routes that avoid the incorrect direct Strecker derivation from acetaldehyde. The dominant route builds the correct branched carbon skeleton first as 3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid (alpha-ketoisovalerate) via pyruvate-centered C-C bond formation and carbonyl rearrangement, then converts that keto acid to valine by reductive amination/transamination in biochemical settings. A secondary convergent route forms 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile (valine aminonitrile) from the correct aldehyde precursor 2-methylpropanal under surface Strecker conditions, followed by hydrolysis to valine. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies CO2 reduction products, pyruvate, acetate, and simple aldehydes; surface chemistry supplies HCN, formaldehyde-derived sugars/carbonyls, branched aldehydes, and aminonitriles; biochemical settings complete amino acid assembly and interconvert hubs. The hub molecules are HCN, pyruvate, 2-methylpropanal, 3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid, and valine aminonitrile, providing dense connectivity and multiple convergent paths.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"HCN\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formic acid/formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-methylpropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-4(2)3-5/h3-4H,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoisovaleric acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"valine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-4(2)5(6)3-7/h4-5H,6H2,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H11NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"valine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Greigite-catalyzed reduction of CO2 to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to a one-carbon carboxylate on iron-sulfur sites.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fe-S minerals are established analogs of acetyl-CoA pathway cofactors and promote CO2 reduction to formate under hydrothermal conditions; this provides a core C1 hub for downstream carbonyl chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Roldan et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Further hydrothermal carbon fixation from formate/CO2 to acetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent, redox gradient across mineral walls\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise CO2-derived C1 reduction and C-C coupling on iron-sulfur surfaces yields C2 carboxylate products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal Fe-S catalysis can access acetate-like products from reduced carbon species and H2, giving a plausible bridge from C1 fixation to small organics relevant to primitive metabolism (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor hydrothermal, anoxic, reducing\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential reduction and C-C bond formation within an Fe-mineral-catalyzed carbon fixation network furnishes the alpha-keto acid pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate is a reported product or near-product in prebiotic reductive carbon fixation models on Fe-bearing hydrothermal catalysts and serves as a central hub linking vent chemistry to amino acid synthesis (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite and Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic mineral surface, NH3 present\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Imine formation between pyruvate and ammonia followed by mineral-assisted reduction generates alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on metal or mineral surfaces is a plausible route to amino acids in vent settings and provides an amino donor reservoir for later transamination chemistry (Barge et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"TiO2-assisted photochemical generation of HCN from reduced C/N feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated subaerial geothermal setting, strongly reducing local microenvironment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoredox activation of carbon and nitrogen feedstocks in reduced surface settings furnishes cyanide/cyanide-equivalent species.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Direct atmospheric and photochemical routes to HCN are more plausible than the previously incorrect simple CO2 + NH3 scheme; this node represents delivery and local photochemical generation in UV-active anoxic settings feeding cyanosulfidic and Strecker chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2016).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface reduction of C1 carbon to formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-illuminated shallow pool, intermittent evaporation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical reduction/dehydration of formate-derived C1 species yields formaldehyde, which is trapped in a surface carbonyl pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Surface photochemistry can convert reduced C1 feedstocks into reactive carbonyls; formaldehyde is a required hub for formose-type sugar and aldehyde chemistry and links hydrothermal formate to surface networks (Sanchez et al., 1967; Cleaves, 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Borate-stabilized formose entry to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool, wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde undergoes base-assisted oligomerization with borate stabilization of carbohydrate products to yield the C2 aldehyde glycolaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Borate minerals stabilize early carbohydrate products in formaldehyde oligomerization, making glycolaldehyde a plausible and recurrent surface hub (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol extension from glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals and clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"intermittent drying concentrates aldehydes\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol condensation between C1 and C2 carbonyls generates the C3 sugar aldehyde glyceraldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aldol-type growth within borate-stabilized formose chemistry yields higher carbonyls, furnishing a plausible route from simple hydrothermal C1 feedstocks to more complex surface aldehydes (Ricardo et al., 2004; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface carbonyl rearrangement to branched aldehyde 2-methylpropanal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles, UV-driven carbonyl isomerization and fragmentation/recombination network\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"A concentrated surface carbonyl network couples pyruvate-derived and sugar-derived carbonyl chemistry to access the branched C4 aldehyde required for valine skeleton encoding.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is explicitly introduced to correct the prior chemically invalid use of acetaldehyde for valine skeleton construction. A branched aldehyde such as 2-methylpropanal is the correct Strecker precursor for valine aminonitrile. The detailed prebiotic path remains partly speculative, but carbonyl network rearrangements under mineral-catalyzed wet-dry and photochemical conditions are plausible and necessary to establish the correct carbon framework (Eschenmoser, 2007; Ritson & Sutherland, 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Branched Strecker synthesis of valine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"shallow pool or tidal flat, concentration by evaporation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The branched aldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, followed by cyanide addition to generate the alpha-aminonitrile corresponding to valine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the chemically correct Strecker branch for valine because 2-methylpropanal, not acetaldehyde, encodes the isopropyl side chain of valine. The step directly addresses the major flaw in earlier attempts (Miller, 1957; Cleaves, 2010).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"geothermal cycling or prolonged aqueous incubation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Progressive nitrile hydration and amide hydrolysis yields the corresponding alpha-amino acid valine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis is a standard completion step for Strecker-derived amino acid synthesis and provides one direct route to valine in prebiotic aqueous environments (Miller, 1957; Parker et al., 2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical branched-chain keto acid synthesis and amination to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mineral interfaces or concentrated prebiotic pools; transamination/reductive amination network\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate-centered carbonyl chemistry generates the branched alpha-keto acid 3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid, which is then aminated using an amino donor reservoir represented by alanine to furnish valine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This node captures the metabolically relevant route to valine through alpha-ketoisovalerate rather than through an incorrect direct aldehyde shortcut. While the exact prebiotic sequence from pyruvate to alpha-ketoisovalerate is less well constrained than biotic valine biosynthesis, alpha-keto acid networking and transamination are chemically plausible and preserve the correct branched-keto-acid logic required for valine formation (Muchowska et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2014).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal keto-acid route to valine\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 fixation to formate, acetate, and pyruvate followed by biochemical branched-chain keto acid formation and amination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation supplies pyruvate and formate; surface chemistry generates HCN and a branched aldehyde, then Strecker synthesis gives valine aminonitrile and hydrolysis gives valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-mediated surface carbonyl pool to valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formate feeds surface formaldehyde formation, then carbonyl evolution reaches the correct branched aldehyde and Strecker chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-first branched aminonitrile route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface cyanide production converges with branched aldehyde generation to form valine aminonitrile and then valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Sugar-assisted pyruvate branching route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface carbohydrate chemistry from formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde collaborates with hydrothermal pyruvate to access the branched aldehyde precursor for valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetate-supported pyruvate-to-ketoisovalerate route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal acetate and pyruvate formation reinforce alpha-keto acid chemistry leading to alpha-ketoisovalerate and valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Alanine-assisted transamination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal alanine formed from pyruvate acts as amino donor within a biochemical network that converts pyruvate-derived branched keto acids to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual-hub convergence at pyruvate and HCN\",\n      \"description\": \"Independent hydrothermal pyruvate formation and surface HCN formation converge downstream through branched aldehyde and aminonitrile chemistry to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface-dominant branched aldehyde route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface carbonyl elaboration from formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde generates a branched aldehyde that enters correct Strecker chemistry to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Network-redundant complete route from CO2 to valine\",\n      \"description\": \"A full cross-environment route beginning with hydrothermal CO2 reduction, feeding both the pyruvate branch and the surface cyanide/carbonyl branch, and ending in biochemical or hydrolytic completion to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Valine", "overall_strategy": "The network targets valine through two chemically distinct but connected prebiotic routes that avoid the incorrect direct Strecker derivation from acetaldehyde. The dominant route builds the correct branched carbon skeleton first as 3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid (alpha-ketoisovalerate) via pyruvate-centered C-C bond formation and carbonyl rearrangement, then converts that keto acid to valine by reductive amination/transamination in biochemical settings. A secondary convergent route forms 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile (valine aminonitrile) from the correct aldehyde precursor 2-methylpropanal under surface Strecker conditions, followed by hydrolysis to valine. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies CO2 reduction products, pyruvate, acetate, and simple aldehydes; surface chemistry supplies HCN, formaldehyde-derived sugars/carbonyls, branched aldehydes, and aminonitriles; biochemical settings complete amino acid assembly and interconvert hubs. The hub molecules are HCN, pyruvate, 2-methylpropanal, 3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid, and valine aminonitrile, providing dense connectivity and multiple convergent paths.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CHN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "acetic acid", "common_name": "acetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C4H8O", "iupac_name": "2-methylpropanal", "common_name": "isobutyraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-4(2)3-5/h3-4H,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H7NO2", "iupac_name": "3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoisovaleric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H10N2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "valine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-4(2)5(6)3-7/h4-5H,6H2,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H11NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "valine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Greigite-catalyzed reduction of CO2 to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to a one-carbon carboxylate on iron-sulfur sites.", "reasoning": "Fe-S minerals are established analogs of acetyl-CoA pathway cofactors and promote CO2 reduction to formate under hydrothermal conditions; this provides a core C1 hub for downstream carbonyl chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Roldan et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Further hydrothermal carbon fixation from formate/CO2 to acetate", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent, redox gradient across mineral walls"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise CO2-derived C1 reduction and C-C coupling on iron-sulfur surfaces yields C2 carboxylate products.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal Fe-S catalysis can access acetate-like products from reduced carbon species and H2, giving a plausible bridge from C1 fixation to small organics relevant to primitive metabolism (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon pool", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor hydrothermal, anoxic, reducing"}, "mechanism": "Sequential reduction and C-C bond formation within an Fe-mineral-catalyzed carbon fixation network furnishes the alpha-keto acid pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate is a reported product or near-product in prebiotic reductive carbon fixation models on Fe-bearing hydrothermal catalysts and serves as a central hub linking vent chemistry to amino acid synthesis (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite and Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic mineral surface, NH3 present"}, "mechanism": "Imine formation between pyruvate and ammonia followed by mineral-assisted reduction generates alanine.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on metal or mineral surfaces is a plausible route to amino acids in vent settings and provides an amino donor reservoir for later transamination chemistry (Barge et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "TiO2-assisted photochemical generation of HCN from reduced C/N feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated subaerial geothermal setting, strongly reducing local microenvironment"}, "mechanism": "Photoredox activation of carbon and nitrogen feedstocks in reduced surface settings furnishes cyanide/cyanide-equivalent species.", "reasoning": "Direct atmospheric and photochemical routes to HCN are more plausible than the previously incorrect simple CO2 + NH3 scheme; this node represents delivery and local photochemical generation in UV-active anoxic settings feeding cyanosulfidic and Strecker chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2016)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface reduction of C1 carbon to formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-illuminated shallow pool, intermittent evaporation"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical reduction/dehydration of formate-derived C1 species yields formaldehyde, which is trapped in a surface carbonyl pool.", "reasoning": "Surface photochemistry can convert reduced C1 feedstocks into reactive carbonyls; formaldehyde is a required hub for formose-type sugar and aldehyde chemistry and links hydrothermal formate to surface networks (Sanchez et al., 1967; Cleaves, 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Borate-stabilized formose entry to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool, wet-dry cycling"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde undergoes base-assisted oligomerization with borate stabilization of carbohydrate products to yield the C2 aldehyde glycolaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Borate minerals stabilize early carbohydrate products in formaldehyde oligomerization, making glycolaldehyde a plausible and recurrent surface hub (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Aldol extension from glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals and clay", "aqueous": "true", "other": "intermittent drying concentrates aldehydes"}, "mechanism": "Aldol condensation between C1 and C2 carbonyls generates the C3 sugar aldehyde glyceraldehyde.", "reasoning": "Aldol-type growth within borate-stabilized formose chemistry yields higher carbonyls, furnishing a plausible route from simple hydrothermal C1 feedstocks to more complex surface aldehydes (Ricardo et al., 2004; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Surface carbonyl rearrangement to branched aldehyde 2-methylpropanal", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and TiO2", 