from the correct aldehyde is one of the strongest features of the network. Unfortunately, the actual generation of that aldehyde is the least convincing part of the entire design, so the pathway remains tentative.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_006\",\n        \"rxn_007\",\n        \"rxn_009\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Develop a more realistic surface route to 2-methylpropanal, potentially via nitrile or hydroxy-acid intermediates\",\n        \"Provide stronger mineral/photochemical justification for each surface carbonyl elaboration step\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.62,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.32,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.45,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.4,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.2,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.86,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.38\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.55,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.67,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.84,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.65,\n      \"feedback\": \"The full network route is commendable for breadth, connectivity, and environmental integration. It clearly reaches valine by two convergent ideas: aminonitrile hydrolysis and keto-acid amination. However, several central reactions are speculative, especially HCN formation from CO2/NH3/H2, formate reduction to formaldehyde, branched aldehyde generation, and the compressed keto-acid-to-valine step. As a complete network it is topologically strong but chemically only moderately convincing.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_006\",\n        \"rxn_007\",\n        \"rxn_009\",\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Rebuild the network around one stronger branch-forming route rather than two under-specified ones\",\n        \"Add explicit mineral agents for every hydrothermal and surface reaction in the full JSON representation\",\n        \"Include literature-supported citations and conditions for key branch-forming reactions\",\n        \"Refine reaction stoichiometry and split multistep transformations into individual nodes\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.66,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"The network is topologically good: it has adequate size, multiple hubs, stated convergence points, and no obvious isolation. It also succeeds at a high level in connecting hydrothermal carbon fixation to surface carbonyl/HCN chemistry and then to biochemical amino-acid assembly. The strongest chemical features are CO2 to formate, plausible early reduced-carbon progression to acetate/pyruvate, pyruvate to alanine, the Strecker conversion of 2-methylpropanal to valine aminonitrile, and aminonitrile hydrolysis to valine. The main weaknesses are several key speculative steps that sit near the center of the network: direct TiO2-assisted generation of HCN from CO2/NH3/H2 is poorly grounded, formate to formaldehyde is underjustified, formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde is oversimplified, pyruvate plus glyceraldehyde to isobutyraldehyde is the least plausible transformation, and the biochemical keto-acid route is compressed into one reaction that conflates carbon-skeleton assembly with amination. Because these weak steps are critical for both convergent routes, no pathway reaches approval despite good overall architecture. Additional concern: the provided summary omits explicit mineral agent specification and detailed conditions per reaction, which are mandatory in the original synthesis-network schema.\",\n  \"approved\": false,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.83,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.79\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": 